<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="60" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="3.[185,1151,413,3274]" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">Remarks. All specimens were taken in the forest, far from water, flying close to the ground or sitting on sticks or stemlets of low growing plants. The larval habitat is unknown. but might not be lotic.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[185,1151,413,3274]" lastBlockId="3.[1271,2235,414,3269]" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">
<taxonomicName authority="Selys" authorityName="DeMarmels" authorityYear="1992" box="[230,640,1757,1794]" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Megapodagrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" sensu="stricto" status="sensu stricto">
<emphasis box="[230,525,1757,1794]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">Megapodagrion</emphasis>
Selys
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[661,914,1757,1794]" pageId="3" pageNumber="60" sensu="stricto">sensu stricto</taxonomicNameLabel>
is monoty pic. Those species included in 
<taxonomicName authority="Forster" authorityName="Forster" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Allopodagrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[882,1149,1810,1847]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">Allopodagrion</emphasis>
Forster
</taxonomicName>
, currentlv considered a subgenus of the former, differ in many important features from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Selys" authorityYear="1862" box="[192,464,1969,2006]" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Megapodagrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="megalopus">
<emphasis box="[192,234,1969,2006]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">M</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[263,464,1969,2006]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">megalopus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis box="[464,469,1969,2006]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">.</emphasis>
Therefore I think that full generic rank for 
<emphasis box="[374,651,2022,2059]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">
<taxonomicName box="[374,645,2022,2059]" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Allopodagrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Allopodagrion</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
as originally assigned to by 
<bibRefCitation author="FORSTER, F." box="[260,523,2067,2113]" journalOrPublisher="Wiener Entomologische Zeitung" pageId="3" pageNumber="60" pagination="51 - 56" part="29" refId="ref10370" refString="FORSTER, F. 1910 - Beitrage zu den Gattungen und Arten der Libellen II. Wiener Entomologische Zeitung, 29: 51 - 56." title="Beitrage zu den Gattungen und Arten der Libellen II" type="journal article" year="1910">Forster (1910)</bibRefCitation>
, is clearly justified. The strongest argument for doing so is given by penis morphology: The penis of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="DeMarmels" authorityYear="1992" box="[718,1012,2180,2217]" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Megapodagrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[718,1012,2180,2217]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">Megapodagrion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is lestine (Fig. 11-12), while that of 
<taxonomicName box="[822,1090,2233,2270]" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Allopodagrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[822,1090,2233,2270]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">Allopodagrion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is typically megapodagrionine (
<figureCitation box="[783,1013,2286,2323]" captionStart="Plate II" captionStartId="14.[193,288,3057,3091]" captionTargetBox="[212,2070,564,2898]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="Plate II: Figure 7. Chalcopteryx scintillans, female ultimate instar exuviae, labium, ventral view. Figures 8-10. Dimeragrion unturanense sp.n. (8) holotype male, abdominal segment 10 with anal appendages, left lateral view; (9) same, dorsal view; (10) female, paratype, tip of abdomen, left lateral view. Figure3 11-12. Megapodagrion megalopus, male. (11) penis, ri.ght lateral view; (12) same, ventral view. Figures 13-14. Allopodagrion oscillans (Venezuela, Tachira, Betania). male. (13) penis, right lateral view; (14) same, ventral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3266069/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">Figs. 13-14</figureCitation>
) with two conspicuos cornua as have, for example, 
<taxonomicName authority="Calvert, Heteragrion Selys" authorityName="Calvert, Heteragrion Selys" authorityYear="1913" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Dimeragrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[193,385,2392,2429]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">Dimeragrion</emphasis>
Calvert, Heteragrion Selys
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Williamson, Philogenia Selys" authorityName="Williamson, Philogenia Selys" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Oxystigma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
Oxystigma Williamson, 
<emphasis box="[440,635,2445,2482]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">Philogenia</emphasis>
Selys
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Racenis. Petiolation" authorityName="Racenis. Petiolation" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Sciotropis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[878,1059,2445,2482]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">Sciotropis</emphasis>
Racenis. Petiolation
</taxonomicName>
of wings ceases far distad from cux in 
<emphasis box="[329,632,2551,2588]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">
<taxonomicName authorityName="DeMarmels" authorityYear="1992" box="[329,625,2551,2588]" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Megapodagrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Megapodagrion</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
but very close to, or even proximally of cux in 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">
<taxonomicName box="[632,902,2604,2641]" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Allopodagrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Allopodagrion</taxonomicName>
. Megapodgrion
</emphasis>
has two supplementary sectors between IR2 and R3 and two more between R3 and IR3 whiIe 
<emphasis box="[245,515,2762,2799]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">Ailopodagrion</emphasis>
has only one in each space. The fore wings are shorter than the hind wings in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="DeMarmels" authorityYear="1992" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Megapodagrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">Megapodagrion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but equal or longer in 
<emphasis box="[874,1147,2868,2905]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">
<taxonomicName box="[874,1142,2868,2905]" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Allopodagrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Allopodagrion</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
Adult 
<taxonomicName authorityName="DeMarmels" authorityYear="1992" box="[320,615,2921,2958]" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Megapodagrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[320,615,2921,2958]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">Megapodagrion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are mottled with brown, the two apical abdominal segments are in thtl male densely covered with white pruinescence Adult 
<taxonomicName box="[322,591,3079,3116]" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Allopodagrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[322,591,3079,3116]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">Allopodagrion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are black with blue patches on the mesepisterna, which might be covered by blue pruinescence, tip of abdomen has no pruinescence. The larval habitat of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="DeMarmels" authorityYear="1992" box="[794,1088,3237,3274]" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Megapodagrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[794,1088,3237,3274]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">Megapodagrion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is unknown, but adults are found in lowland rain forest away from running water flying close to the ground. All species of 
<taxonomicName box="[1720,1989,520,557]" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Allopodagrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1720,1989,520,557]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">Allopodagrion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are instead breeding in small mountain creeks in partly open or closed forest and do not abandon the water courses. It seems, therefore, that besides of the long legs, 
<taxonomicName box="[1470,1740,732,769]" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Allopodagrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1470,1740,732,769]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">Allopodagrion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
does not share more characters with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="DeMarmels" authorityYear="1992" box="[1517,1811,784,821]" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Megapodagrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1517,1811,784,821]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">Megapodagrion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
than with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Selys" authorityYear="1862" box="[2034,2227,784,821]" class="Insecta" family="Megapodagrionidae" genus="Philogenia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Philogenia</taxonomicName>
or with any other of the compared genera
</paragraph>
